  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone can break down cell membranes primarily due to its solvent properties and its ability to interact with the lipids that make up these membranes. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Solubility in Lipids**: Acetone is an organic solvent that is miscible with water and soluble in many lipids. It can dissolve lipids, which are the primary components of cell membranes. The phospholipid bilayer, which forms the structure of cell membranes, consists of hydrophilic (water-attracting) heads and hydrophobic (water-repelling) tails. Acetone can disrupt the interactions between these lipid molecules.\n\n2. **Disruption of Membrane Structure**: When acetone interacts with the lipid bilayer, it can insert itself between the lipid molecules, disturbing the ordered structure of the bilayer. This disruption increases fluidity and permeability, causing the membrane to lose its integrity.\n\n3. **Protein Denaturation**: In addition to lipids, membranes also contain proteins that help maintain its structure and function. Acetone may denature some of these proteins, further compromising the integrity of the cell membrane.\n\nThe combined effect of these actions can lead to increased permeability of the membrane, which can cause leakage of cellular contents or prevent the membrane from performing its essential barrier functions, ultimately leading to cell damage or cell death. This solvent effect of acetone is why it is often used in laboratories to permeabilize cell membranes or extract lipid compounds.",
